1
00:00:20,854 --> 00:00:26,315
<i>I'm Lars, and I'm sitting here</i>
<i>with Peter Aalbæk, who is</i> - 

2
00:00:26,526 --> 00:00:30,519
<i>Well, how were you involved</i>
<i>in this film?</i>

3
00:00:30,730 --> 00:00:33,426
<i>Well,</i>

4
00:00:33,633 --> 00:00:38,935
<i>I think I was</i> - <i>I was probably</i>
<i>what you'd call a producer.</i>

5
00:00:39,139 --> 00:00:43,599
<i>A producer?</i>
<i>Not an executive producer?</i>

6
00:00:43,810 --> 00:00:49,407
<i>As you probably remember, I'd just</i>
<i>gone bankrupt with my company,</i>

7
00:00:49,616 --> 00:00:53,017
<i>which had received</i>
<i>the first money for the film.</i>

8
00:00:54,220 --> 00:00:57,189
<i>- And the money just disappeared?</i>
<i>- No.</i>

9
00:00:58,124 --> 00:01:00,422
<i>You and Niels Vørsel</i>
<i>got the money,</i>

10
00:01:00,627 --> 00:01:05,291
<i>but the Film Institute told me they</i>
<i>wouldn't let me produce the film.</i>

11
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:12,767
<i>- They didn't stick to that decision.</i>
<i>- They probably should have.</i>

12
00:01:12,972 --> 00:01:19,605
<i>Then we were told that we had</i>
<i>to find some new investors.</i>

13
00:01:20,814 --> 00:01:25,308
<i>We sent the script to Per Holst,</i>
<i>your former executive producer.</i>

14
00:01:25,518 --> 00:01:32,253
<i>Yes, and somehow it didn't fit</i>
<i>into his "repertoire plans."</i>

15
00:01:32,459 --> 00:01:36,725
<i>After having produced</i>
The Element of Crime -

16
00:01:38,698 --> 00:01:40,791
<i>Which he lost a lot of money on.</i>

17
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:46,495
<i>Our script was lying on</i>
<i>his table for six months,</i>

18
00:01:46,706 --> 00:01:48,901
<i>when we finally got a letter</i>- 

19
00:01:49,109 --> 00:01:55,673
<i>It was a standard letter, and at the</i>
<i>bottom of the page they'd written</i>

20
00:01:55,882 --> 00:02:00,251
<i>that "it didn't fit into the</i>
<i>repertoire plans of Per Holst Film. "</i>

21
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:03,911
<i>What kind of executive producer</i>
<i>has a repertoire plan?</i>

22
00:02:05,291 --> 00:02:07,623
<i>Apparently,</i>
<i>Per Holst had at the time.</i>

23
00:02:09,329 --> 00:02:11,456
<i>It didn't fit into his golf plans.</i>

24
00:02:12,665 --> 00:02:15,031
<i>We also spoke to Metronome.</i>

25
00:02:15,235 --> 00:02:20,867
<i>And Mads loved the script.</i>
<i>- They all did.</i>

26
00:02:21,074 --> 00:02:25,977
<i>The most interesting concerning this</i> - 
<i>Do you remember Metz?</i>

27
00:02:26,179 --> 00:02:29,580
<i>Yeah, Metz,</i>
<i>goddamn it, that was</i> - 

28
00:02:29,682 --> 00:02:33,448
<i>Metz had this interesting viewpoint.</i>

29
00:02:33,653 --> 00:02:38,056
<i>He thought</i>
<i>it was a very interesting project,</i>

30
00:02:38,258 --> 00:02:41,659
<i>but he wouldn't</i>
<i>invest any money in it.</i>

31
00:02:41,861 --> 00:02:45,319
<i>It didn't fit into his</i>
<i>repertoire plans either.</i>

32
00:02:45,532 --> 00:02:48,524
<i>We were having lunch,</i>

33
00:02:48,735 --> 00:02:54,173
<i>which I paid for</i>- 
<i>Or did he actually pay for it?</i>

34
00:02:54,374 --> 00:02:57,400
<i>Film consultants</i>
<i>never buy you anything.</i>

35
00:02:57,610 --> 00:03:01,341
<i>They just want the receipt,</i>
<i>but they never buy you anything.</i>

36
00:03:01,548 --> 00:03:06,417
<i>Anyway, he told me</i>
<i>how much he liked the script,</i>

37
00:03:06,619 --> 00:03:13,991
<i>and then he said that he would</i>
<i>never invest any money in the film.</i>

38
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:17,755
<i>The next day I went to Nordisk Film</i>

39
00:03:17,964 --> 00:03:20,762
<i>and told Bahs</i>
<i>we wouldn't get any money.</i>

40
00:03:20,967 --> 00:03:27,202
<i>Then he said, "It's been discussed at</i>
<i>a meeting this morning. It's okay. "</i>

41
00:03:27,407 --> 00:03:34,370
<i>Apparently, all the big bosses at</i>
<i>Nordisk Film went to these meetings.</i>

42
00:03:34,581 --> 00:03:40,679
<i>In the credits it says:</i>
<i>"George Metz helped finance this film."</i>

43
00:03:40,887 --> 00:03:46,382
<i>I've never spoken to Metz about it,</i>
<i>but it was a dramatic change in</i> - 

44
00:03:47,527 --> 00:03:52,089
<i>But then again, I'd only heard</i>
<i>him say that he wouldn't support it.</i>

45
00:03:52,298 --> 00:03:55,790
<i>Because he wanted</i>
<i>to make the film</i> Sofie.

46
00:03:56,002 --> 00:04:01,099
<i>When Nordisk Film decided to support</i>
<i>that film, he supported this one.</i>

47
00:04:01,307 --> 00:04:05,243
<i>- Was it a "package deal"?</i>
<i>- Definitely.</i>

48
00:04:05,445 --> 00:04:10,075
<i>Isn't that wrong and</i>
<i>something you should never do?</i>

49
00:04:10,283 --> 00:04:15,243
<i>Well, the Film Institute refused to</i>
<i>make a deal on the Dogme films,</i>

50
00:04:15,455 --> 00:04:17,582
<i>because we asked them directly.</i>

51
00:04:17,790 --> 00:04:21,920
Europa <i>and</i> Sofie <i>were</i>
<i>the results of an unofficial request.</i>

52
00:04:22,128 --> 00:04:24,926
<i>There's Ernst-Hugo!</i>

53
00:04:25,131 --> 00:04:26,826
<i>Oh, now you're talking</i>
<i>about the film?</i>

54
00:04:31,471 --> 00:04:35,498
<i>There's a film studio in Ystad</i>
<i>called "Ernst-Hugo."</i>

55
00:04:35,708 --> 00:04:40,839
<i>Really?</i>
<i>Sweet Ernst-Hugo. I miss him.</i>

56
00:04:42,815 --> 00:04:44,783
<i>"You may embrace me."</i>

57
00:04:46,519 --> 00:04:52,458
<i>Back then, Jean-Marc still had</i>
<i>a few sticky locks.</i>

58
00:04:52,859 --> 00:04:55,623
<i>Since then,</i>
<i>it's gone from bad to worse.</i>

59
00:04:55,828 --> 00:04:57,853
<i>The technical</i>- 

60
00:04:58,064 --> 00:05:02,933
<i>You can't tell they're walking</i>
<i>on a moving platform here, right?</i>

61
00:05:03,136 --> 00:05:06,435
<i>Well, why bother making it</i> - 

62
00:05:06,639 --> 00:05:11,440
<i>If you can't tell it's fake?</i>
<i>You're absolutely right.</i>

63
00:05:11,644 --> 00:05:15,876
<i>I believe the background is from</i> - 

64
00:05:16,082 --> 00:05:20,951
<i>We talked about Breslaw, Wroclaw</i>- 
<i>Or was it Stettin?</i>

65
00:05:22,155 --> 00:05:28,958
<i>Well, all the backgrounds are shot</i>
<i>in Poland and this is a back projection.</i>

66
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:32,029
<i>It's a front projection.</i>

67
00:05:32,231 --> 00:05:36,395
<i>This is a Henning Bahs set.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

68
00:05:36,602 --> 00:05:43,701
<i>And we used the city hall windows</i>
<i>from an old Olsen Gang film.</i>

69
00:05:43,910 --> 00:05:48,472
<i>Bahs was very proud of this.</i>
<i>In one of the Olsen Gang films</i>

70
00:05:48,681 --> 00:05:52,242
<i>they're looking through</i>
<i>the windows of the city hall.</i>

71
00:05:52,452 --> 00:05:54,977
<i>He pulled them out of storage</i>

72
00:05:55,188 --> 00:06:00,592
<i>and they probably charged us</i>
<i>a lot of money to let us use them.</i>

73
00:06:00,793 --> 00:06:03,387
<i>I know we would have.</i>

74
00:06:03,596 --> 00:06:07,589
<i>- Don't talk about "us" as if</i>- 
<i>- As if we're a unity?</i>

75
00:06:08,868 --> 00:06:13,362
<i>Especially right now.</i>
<i>Did you see that detail?</i>

76
00:06:13,573 --> 00:06:17,907
<i>By the way, that was Leif Magnusson,</i>
<i>now we're talking about</i> - 

77
00:06:18,111 --> 00:06:22,673
<i>The detail was the mirror which</i>
<i>is covered when it's brought in.</i>

78
00:06:22,882 --> 00:06:25,544
<i>I've never seen that before.</i>

79
00:06:25,752 --> 00:06:30,689
<i>No, but we saved you the trouble</i>
<i>of making a hidden camera.</i>

80
00:06:30,890 --> 00:06:35,452
<i>You don't know this, but we try</i>
<i>really hard to minimize the expenses.</i>

81
00:06:35,561 --> 00:06:39,053
<i>To see Henning Bendtsen</i>
<i>behind the box.</i>

82
00:06:39,265 --> 00:06:41,529
<i>Behind a Panavision camera.</i>

83
00:06:41,734 --> 00:06:46,967
<i>Yes, and that camera type</i>
<i>is called a Panaflex.</i>

84
00:06:51,244 --> 00:06:55,237
<i>And it's shot in Panavision.</i>
<i>- I see.</i>

85
00:06:56,949 --> 00:06:59,782
<i>Ernst-Hugo was a nice guy.</i>

86
00:07:05,525 --> 00:07:06,992
<i>Yes, he was.</i>

87
00:07:07,193 --> 00:07:10,890
<i>I'd seen him</i>
<i>in a Swedish television series</i>

88
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:15,659
<i>where he played a red-haired police</i>
<i>officer who'd killed his parents.</i>

89
00:07:16,869 --> 00:07:22,000
<i>We needed a Swedish actor because</i>
<i>the Swedes helped finance the film.</i>

90
00:07:22,975 --> 00:07:24,567
<i>You've always been great at that.</i>

91
00:07:25,344 --> 00:07:32,273
<i>And it was very peculiar that</i>
<i>a taxi from Lidingö to the airport</i>

92
00:07:32,485 --> 00:07:40,449
<i>could cost 1,305 Swedish kroner.</i>
<i>That record still stands.</i>

93
00:07:40,660 --> 00:07:44,323
<i>We've worked with</i>
<i>Philip Zandén and other Swedes</i> - 

94
00:07:44,530 --> 00:07:48,933
<i>He's never managed</i>
<i>to spend that much on a taxi.</i>

95
00:07:49,135 --> 00:07:53,663
<i>But I've always been told to</i>
<i>believe the things people tell me.</i>

96
00:07:53,873 --> 00:07:56,740
<i>This is a split screen</i>
<i>with a model of a dormitory.</i>

97
00:07:56,843 --> 00:07:59,403
<i>Yes, I remember that.</i>
<i>The model.</i>

98
00:07:59,512 --> 00:08:02,709
<i>It was difficult to make.</i>
<i>We should have just used a real dormitory.</i>

99
00:08:02,815 --> 00:08:05,147
- <i>With a lot of beds.</i>
- <i>Yes.</i>

100
00:08:05,251 --> 00:08:08,584
<i>I'm sure Ernst-Hugo</i>
<i>spat in his face there.</i>

101
00:08:11,424 --> 00:08:16,418
<i>This was the common</i> - 
<i>What kind of head did we use here?</i>

102
00:08:16,629 --> 00:08:22,795
<i>What are those heads called that</i>
<i>you can operate by remote control?</i>

103
00:08:23,002 --> 00:08:28,668
<i>- Do you think we used them here?</i>
<i>- I'm not sure.</i>

104
00:08:28,875 --> 00:08:33,869
<i>Later, when they walk around inside</i>
<i>the house, we used that apparatus.</i>

105
00:08:34,881 --> 00:08:38,977
<i>It's almost standard nowadays.</i>
<i>The young people</i> - 

106
00:08:39,185 --> 00:08:42,848
<i>- They have all the latest technology.</i>
<i>- And know how to use it.</i>

107
00:08:46,225 --> 00:08:50,628
<i>Look. There we use</i>
<i>an extended silhouette effect.</i>

108
00:08:51,497 --> 00:08:55,490
<i>That was back when</i>
<i>the pictures mattered to you.</i>

109
00:08:57,403 --> 00:09:01,840
<i>What's her name?</i>
<i>- It's Vera Gebuhr.</i>

110
00:09:02,041 --> 00:09:05,477
<i>She's been in all my films.</i>

111
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:13,884
<i>Most of the actors claimed that</i>
<i>they were fluent in German,</i>

112
00:09:14,086 --> 00:09:17,112
<i>but she was one of the only ones</i>
<i>who actually spoke the language.</i>

113
00:09:18,024 --> 00:09:22,051
<i>In</i> Dancer <i>Paprika Steen told me</i>
<i>she could speak English.</i>

114
00:09:22,261 --> 00:09:26,095
<i>That was also interesting.</i>
<i>- That was a lie!</i>

115
00:09:26,198 --> 00:09:31,534
<i>Her mother is American,</i>
<i>and therefore she thought</i> - 

116
00:09:31,737 --> 00:09:33,204
<i>That was quite funny.</i>

117
00:09:35,474 --> 00:09:41,845
<i>And Jørgen Reenberg thought</i>
<i>he mastered German perfectly.</i>

118
00:09:42,048 --> 00:09:43,948
<i>Yes, he thought</i>
<i>he was infallible.</i>

119
00:09:49,221 --> 00:09:53,920
<i>It was because he spoke German</i>
<i>to his dog, as hunters often do.</i>

120
00:09:54,126 --> 00:09:59,564
<i>- And he was really good at it.</i>
<i>- Yes,</i> "hinter" <i>and</i> "Sitz."

121
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:02,734
<i>Look! Now we're</i> - 
<i>- Back in Poland.</i>

122
00:10:05,671 --> 00:10:11,337
<i>When we shot these backgrounds</i>
<i>we hadn't found all the actors yet.</i>

123
00:10:11,544 --> 00:10:16,174
<i>This is, of course,</i>
<i>a front projection.</i>

124
00:10:16,382 --> 00:10:23,788
<i>But the extras,</i>
<i>or the stand-ins, we used</i> - 

125
00:10:23,990 --> 00:10:27,892
<i>Later on we had to find some actors</i>
<i>who looked like those extras.</i>

126
00:10:27,994 --> 00:10:33,626
<i>Well, that approach</i>
<i>might be as good as any.</i>

127
00:10:33,833 --> 00:10:37,325
<i>Who was he?</i>
<i>The guy to the right?</i>

128
00:10:37,536 --> 00:10:42,496
<i>He was a cultural official</i>
<i>in some German city.</i>

129
00:10:42,708 --> 00:10:47,202
<i>- He was really good.</i>
<i>- He wasn't an actor.</i>

130
00:10:47,413 --> 00:10:50,382
<i>He was a cultural official,</i>
<i>whatever that means.</i>

131
00:10:56,389 --> 00:11:02,328
<i>Many of the actors were</i>
<i>reluctant to participate in the film.</i>

132
00:11:05,698 --> 00:11:10,431
<i>You weren't that hot back then.</i>

133
00:11:10,636 --> 00:11:14,163
<i>Neither was the producer.</i>

134
00:11:14,373 --> 00:11:17,706
<i>That was what united us then.</i>

135
00:11:17,910 --> 00:11:22,745
<i>Our despondency and lack of</i>
<i>sympathy from the world around us.</i>

136
00:11:22,948 --> 00:11:28,079
<i>And from one another. And now we've</i>
<i>reached the end of a curve again.</i>

137
00:11:29,021 --> 00:11:36,120
<i>A curve. And you try to curve</i>
<i>your way around</i> - 

138
00:11:36,328 --> 00:11:39,786
<i>What's it called</i> - <i>the thing</i>
<i>that moves the trains around?</i>

139
00:11:39,899 --> 00:11:43,391
<i>The turntable.</i>
<i>It symbolizes our cooperation.</i>

140
00:11:43,602 --> 00:11:47,299
<i>I stand with the handle and you just</i>
<i>stand there talking nonsense.</i>

141
00:11:48,274 --> 00:11:54,509
<i>No, he talks about</i>
<i>the sleeping car, which</i> - 

142
00:11:56,315 --> 00:11:59,910
<i>Here are all</i>
<i>the freezing cold, Polish children.</i>

143
00:12:00,019 --> 00:12:04,115
<i>The problem here was</i>

144
00:12:04,323 --> 00:12:07,986
<i>that they're pulling a real carriage.</i>

145
00:12:08,194 --> 00:12:12,324
<i>We put a small locomotive behind it</i>
<i>to help push it forward,</i>

146
00:12:12,531 --> 00:12:15,159
<i>but they could</i>
<i>easily pull it themselves,</i>

147
00:12:15,367 --> 00:12:18,336
<i>thus we had to add</i>
<i>an extra carriage.</i>

148
00:12:18,537 --> 00:12:22,303
<i>Apparently, it's very easy</i>
<i>to pull such a carriage.</i>

149
00:12:22,508 --> 00:12:24,999
<i>Ten men could pull it</i>
<i>by themselves.</i>

150
00:12:25,211 --> 00:12:30,843
<i>Well, you must take off your hat</i>
<i>to the art of engineering.</i>

151
00:12:31,050 --> 00:12:37,421
<i>Yes. It caught us by surprise.</i>
<i>Even Henning Bahs was surprised.</i>

152
00:12:38,858 --> 00:12:45,764
<i>That wasn’t the carriage.</i>
<i>No, we bought one.</i>

153
00:12:45,965 --> 00:12:49,958
<i>We never used the carriage.</i>
<i>That one has just been painted on.</i>

154
00:12:52,171 --> 00:12:56,198
<i>We bought the interior of a carriage.</i>

155
00:12:56,408 --> 00:13:00,037
<i>Bahs bought the interior of</i>
<i>a carriage for 10 dollars in Poland.</i>

156
00:13:01,781 --> 00:13:03,806
<i>Ernst-Hugo drops a tear there.</i>

157
00:13:13,659 --> 00:13:21,259
<i>Do you remember that the investors</i>
<i>demanded we make it in color?</i>

158
00:13:21,367 --> 00:13:26,236
<i>- No, I haven't seen any colors yet.</i>
<i>- They appear later on.</i>

159
00:13:28,207 --> 00:13:32,735
<i>No, I don't remember.</i>
<i>Once more, the director has</i> - 

160
00:13:32,845 --> 00:13:35,177
<i>Cheated the investors.</i>

161
00:13:35,381 --> 00:13:38,873
<i>I thought you talked</i>
<i>about my loss of integrity.</i>

162
00:13:39,084 --> 00:13:42,645
<i>You've claimed that I've lost it</i>
<i>so many times since.</i>

163
00:13:44,089 --> 00:13:50,358
<i>No, they demanded it become</i>
<i>a color film, and then you said,</i>

164
00:13:50,563 --> 00:13:57,025
<i>"Okay, we'll make four shots</i>
<i>in color, end of story. "</i>

165
00:14:01,273 --> 00:14:02,672
<i>It was a bit more</i> - 

166
00:14:02,775 --> 00:14:05,107
<i>- That was very resolute.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

167
00:14:06,078 --> 00:14:08,103
<i>Look!</i>

168
00:14:08,314 --> 00:14:13,581
<i>That carriage is made up of</i>
<i>the detached parts bought in Poland.</i>

169
00:14:14,954 --> 00:14:19,891
<i>It was a beautiful carriage,</i>
<i>which had been</i> - 

170
00:14:20,092 --> 00:14:25,462
<i>Bahs made sure that all the parts</i>
<i>of the carriages could be removed.</i>

171
00:14:25,664 --> 00:14:28,792
<i>We installed the camera</i>
<i>in the ceiling</i>

172
00:14:29,001 --> 00:14:32,596
<i>so the carriage could move</i>
<i>from side to side,</i>

173
00:14:32,805 --> 00:14:39,074
<i>without touching</i>
<i>the camera suspension.</i>

174
00:14:39,278 --> 00:14:44,807
<i>I'm sure we've got</i>
<i>some pictures of it somewhere.</i>

175
00:14:45,017 --> 00:14:48,817
<i>From time to time,</i>
<i>I was rocking the carriage.</i>

176
00:14:49,021 --> 00:14:57,326
<i>You moved it with a big beam,</i>
<i>using "the principle of the lever."</i>

177
00:14:57,529 --> 00:15:04,628
<i>I did it with Jørgen Johansen, who</i>
<i>became our cameraman later on.</i>

178
00:15:04,837 --> 00:15:09,137
<i>He probably should have stuck</i>
<i>with the beam.</i>

